Network Defense & Countermeasures ‚Äì Session 3
BASIC MCQs (1‚Äì10)
1. Packet filtering firewalls make decisions based on:
A. Application content
B. User identity
C. IP address, port, and protocol
D. Payload inspection

2. Packet filtering firewalls primarily operate at which OSI layers?
A. Physical and Data Link
B. Network and Transport
C. Session and Presentation
D. Application only

3. A screened host firewall typically consists of:
A. Only a packet filter
B. Packet filter + bastion host
C. IDS + IPS
D. Proxy server only

4. The main role of a bastion host is to:
A. Improve network speed
B. Act as a hardened system exposed to the internet
C. Store sensitive data
D. Replace internal servers

5. Stateful inspection firewall differs from packet filtering by:
A. Blocking all traffic
B. Tracking connection state
C. Working only at application layer
D. Using proxy architecture

6. Which firewall keeps track of TCP session states like SYN, ACK, FIN?
A. Packet filter
B. Proxy firewall
C. Stateful firewall
D. Application firewall

7. Next Generation Firewalls (NGFW) mainly extend capabilities by adding:
A. NAT only
B. App-level control and visibility
C. Routing protocols
D. Packet sniffing

8. iptables is best described as:
A. IDS tool
B. Application proxy
C. Linux kernel-based firewall framework
D. Antivirus software

9. Which iptables chain handles traffic destined for the local system?
A. FORWARD
B. POSTROUTING
C. INPUT
D. OUTPUT

10. The default policy in iptables defines:
A. Order of rule execution
B. Action when no rule matches
C. Packet logging level
D. Table priority

INTERMEDIATE MCQs (11‚Äì20)
11. A major limitation of packet filtering firewalls is that they:
A. Consume excessive CPU
B. Cannot track session state
C. Cannot block IP addresses
D. Work only on TCP

12. In a screened host firewall architecture, where is the bastion host placed?
A. Internal LAN
B. DMZ or behind packet filter
C. WAN only
D. Core switch

13. Which firewall type provides better protection against IP spoofing?
A. Packet filter
B. Stateful inspection firewall
C. Static firewall
D. Hub

14. NextGen firewalls can block traffic based on:
A. Only port numbers
B. Only IP addresses
C. Application identity (e.g., Facebook, BitTorrent)
D. MAC address only

15. Which iptables table is used for basic packet filtering?
A. nat
B. mangle
C. filter
D. raw

16. Which chain is evaluated for packets passing through the system (not destined locally)?
A. INPUT
B. OUTPUT
C. FORWARD
D. PREROUTING

17. If no iptables rule matches and default policy is DROP, the packet will be:
A. Logged and forwarded
B. Accepted
C. Dropped
D. Redirected

18. Stateful firewall inspection mainly improves security by:
A. Encrypting packets
B. Tracking connection context
C. Filtering based on payload
D. Acting as proxy

19. Which NGFW feature helps control SaaS application misuse?
A. NAT
B. App Control
C. Static routing
D. Port forwarding

20. iptables processes rules in which order?
A. Random order
B. Bottom to top
C. Top to bottom
D. Based on packet size

ADVANCED MCQs (21‚Äì30)
21. In iptables, which action immediately stops rule processing in a chain?
A. LOG
B. DROP
C. ACCEPT
D. RETURN

22. A packet enters a Linux firewall and is destined for another network. Which chain is MOST relevant?
A. INPUT
B. OUTPUT
C. FORWARD
D. POSTROUTING

23. Screened host firewall architecture improves security mainly by:
A. Eliminating internal routing
B. Adding layered defense
C. Removing need for firewall rules
D. Increasing bandwidth

24. NGFW application awareness is particularly effective against:
A. IP spoofing
B. Port-hopping applications
C. ARP poisoning
D. MAC flooding

25. Which scenario best demonstrates stateful inspection?
A. Blocking packets by port number
B. Allowing return traffic for established connections
C. Filtering based on URL
D. Blocking malformed packets only

26. In iptables, incorrect rule ordering can result in:
A. Kernel crash
B. Security bypass
C. Packet corruption
D. CPU overheating

27. Which table is processed FIRST by iptables?
A. filter
B. nat
C. raw
D. mangle

28. NGFW differs from traditional firewalls because it:
A. Operates only at layer 3
B. Combines firewall, IPS, and app control
C. Eliminates need for DMZ
D. Works without rules

29. A default ACCEPT policy with poor rule design is risky because it:
A. Drops valid traffic
B. Allows unintended traffic
C. Breaks routing
D. Disables logging

30. From CDAC CCEE viewpoint, iptables is BEST described as:
A. GUI-based firewall only
B. User-space packet analyzer
C. Rule-based packet filtering framework
D. IDS replacement

ANSWER KEY
Basic:
1-C, 2-B, 3-B, 4-B, 5-B, 6-C, 7-B, 8-C, 9-C, 10-B

Intermediate:
11-B, 12-B, 13-B, 14-C, 15-C, 16-C, 17-C, 18-B, 19-B, 20-C

Advanced:
21-D, 22-C, 23-B, 24-B, 25-B, 26-B, 27-C, 28-B, 29-B, 30-C

